Day 37: Managing EC2 Access with S3 Role-based Permissions
Task:

1) EC2 Instance Setup:

An instance named devops-ec2 already exists.
The instance requires access to an S3 bucket.
2) Setup SSH Keys:

Create new SSH key pair (id_rsa and id_rsa.pub) on the aws-client host and add the public key to the root user's authorized keys on the EC2 instance.
3) Create a Private S3 Bucket:

Name the bucket devops-s3-849502589868.
Ensure the bucket is private.
4) Create an IAM Policy and Role:

Create an IAM policy allowing s3:PutObject, s3:ListBucket and s3:GetObject access to devops-s3-849502589868.
Create an IAM role named devops-role.
Attach the policy to the IAM role.
Attach this role to the devops-ec2 instance.
5) Test the Access:

SSH into the EC2 instance and try to upload a file to devops-s3-849502589868 bucket using following command:
aws s3 cp <your-file> s3://devops-s3-849502589868/

Now run following command to list the upload file:
aws s3 ls s3://devops-s3-849502589868/

###Solution 

Step 1: Setup SSH Key Pair on aws-client
Since this part happens on your local aws-client machine, the steps are the same:
Open terminal on aws-client host.
Run:
ssh-keygen -t rsa -b 2048 -f ~/.ssh/id_rsa

Step 2: Create Private S3 Bucket
Go to AWS Management Console → S3 → Create Bucket.
Bucket Name: devops-s3-849502589868
Region: Choose your region (e.g., us-east-1)
Object Ownership: ACLs disabled (recommended)
Block Public Access Settings: Keep all checked → makes bucket private
Click Create Bucket

Step 3: Create IAM Policy
Go to IAM → Policies → Create Policy
Switch to JSON tab and paste:

{
  "Version": "2012-10-17",
  "Statement": [
    {
      "Effect": "Allow",
      "Action": [
        "s3:PutObject",
        "s3:GetObject",
        "s3:ListBucket"
      ],
      "Resource": [
        "arn:aws:s3:::devops-s3-849502589868",
        "arn:aws:s3:::devops-s3-849502589868/*"
      ]
    }
  ]
}

Click Next → Tags → Next → Review
Name: devops-s3-policy → Create Policy


Step 4: Create IAM Role and Attach Policy
Go to IAM → Roles → Create Role
Select AWS service → EC2 → Next
Attach existing policy → search for devops-s3-policy → check it → Next
Name role: devops-role → Create Role

Step 5: Attach Role to EC2 Instance
Go to EC2 → Instances → select devops-ec2 → Actions → Security → Modify IAM Role
Select IAM role: devops-role → Save
✅ Now the EC2 instance has S3 permissions via the role.

Step 6: Test S3 Access
SSH into EC2 using your new private key:
ssh -i ~/.ssh/id_rsa root@<EC2_PUBLIC_IP>
Upload a file:
echo "Hello DevOps" > test.txt
aws s3 cp test.txt s3://devops-s3-849502589868/
List bucket contents:
aws s3 ls s3://devops-s3-849502589868/
✅ You should see test.txt listed, meaning your role-based permissions are working.
